// ICE & THERMAL EFFECTS ON DIFFERENT SUBSTANCES:
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// EFFECT TYPE         | TEMPERATURE     | VISUAL APPEARANCE      | WHEN IT OCCURS
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// melting-ice         | 0°C to -10°C    | Solid→Liquid (clear)   | Ice melting, phase change starts
// frosting            | -20°C to -60°C  | White frost coat forms | Water vapor condenses and freezes on surface
// sublimation-frost   | -30°C to -78°C  | Dry ice fog/white mist | Solid directly to gas (dry ice effect)  
// ice-formation       | -50°C or lower  | Ice crystals visible   | Water freezing rapidly on container
// condensation        | -15°C to 0°C    | Beads of water forming | Atmospheric moisture freezing
// vapor-fog           | -40°C to -78°C  | Cold visible gas cloud | Sublimating vapor visible (I₂ purple fog)
// glassy-crust        | -30°C or lower  | Shiny frozen surface   | Solution freezing into solid glassy layer
// effervescent-cold   | -20°C or lower  | Bubbling + frost       | Gas release + rapid cooling simultaneously
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 
// EFFECTS ON DIFFERENT CHEMICAL TYPES:
// • Water/Ice: Melts at 0°C, sublimes as frost, forms ice crystals at -50°C+
// • Salts: Absorb water from air (hygroscopic), crystallize as temp drops
// • Gases: Condense visibly below -30°C (CO₂ produces thick fog)
// • Liquids: Develop ice crust when endothermic cooling is extreme
// • Solids: Form glassy coating when surface temperature drops rapidly
//
// HEAT ABSORPTION INTENSITY SCALE (related to temperature change):
// Intensity 2-3: Mild cooling (-8 to -25°C)  → Slight condensation
// Intensity 4-5: Moderate cooling (-25 to -40°C) → Frosting visible
// Intensity 6-7: Strong cooling (-40 to -60°C) → Ice formation, thick frost
// Intensity 8+: Extreme cooling (-60 to -90°C) → Dry ice-like effects, water freezes solid
//
